\ul Why use a 64-bit kernel?\ulnone \
\
Because it's faster. The 64-bit kernel significantly improves I/O across the board, because the kernel can hold much larger caches without running into the 4 GB VRAM limit of 32-bit processes. It also supports addressing large amounts of video RAM, and several other things. In addition, the AMD/Intel 64-bit CPU architecture contains a number of performance improvements over the older 32-bit CPU architecture that will make the kernel run slightly faster internally.\
\
Note that not all 64-bit architectures are faster. Nintendo's Nintendo 64 game console, for example, shipped with a 64-bit CPU, but almost all software for the console ran in 32-bit mode for performance reasons. The AMD/Intel 64-bit architecture is something of an anomaly here; if you want more details, then read the "AMD64" article on Wikipedia.\
\
The downside is, because the 64-bit kernel is a brand new feature of Snow Leopard, a lot of first- and third-party kernel extensions aren't available for the 64-bit kernel yet, most notably the myriad of kernel extensions that ship with Apple's Final Cut and Logic products. If you use software that depends on 32-bit kernel extensions, then you cannot use the 64-bit kernel yet, sorry.\
\
Also, using the 64-bit kernel may break some applications that depended on the contents of the sysctl key "hw.machine" to be "i386" (meaning Intel 32-bit) on Intel Macs, but this is not common.\
\
Also, the 64-bit kernel does use slightly more physical RAM due to the larger caches and larger pointer sizes, but unless you have an extreme RAM shortage, you probably won't notice the difference.\
\
Note that, even if the kernel is running in 64-bit mode, Mac OS X still supports launching 32-bit applications. Only kernel extensions are affected.\
\
\
\ul Why use a 32-bit kernel?\ulnone \
\
By default, unless you're using a 2008 or later model Mac Pro or Xserve, then the kernel starts up in 32-bit mode. 32-bit mode ensures maximum compatibility with older kernel extensions that haven't been written for the 64-bit kernel yet.\
\
Note that, even if the kernel is running in 32-bit mode, Mac OS X still supports launching 64-bit applications, and still supports addressing more than 4 GB of physical RAM through PAE (Physical Address Extension). Only kernel extensions are affected.\
\
\
\ul How do I tell if the 64-bit kernel is running or not?\ulnone \
\
In Activity Monitor, set the window to show all processes, then look for the process with a PID value of 0. This is the kernel. If the process kind is "Intel (64 bit)", then it means that the 64-bit kernel is in use. If the process kind is just "Intel", then it means that the 32-bit kernel is in use. (If you don't see the PID or Kind table columns, you can turn them on in the View menu.)\
\
\
\ul Does going 64-bit inhibit my computer's ability to boot into other 32-bit kernels (Leopard, Windows XP, etc.)?\ulnone \
\
No; the setting is only honored by Snow Leopard & later. In other words, if you set Snow Leopard to boot the 64-bit kernel, and you go back to Leopard for some reason, then Leopard will boot normally.\
\
\
\ul What's with the icon?\ulnone \
\
Yes, I intentionally chose to go with a retro icon. The icon is a tribute to Connectix's MODE32 system extension.\
\
For those of you who weren't Mac users back when Mac OS 7 came out in 1991, Mac OS 7 added support for 32-bit addressing, but Apple shipped several 32-bit computers that couldn't use it because of design flaws. MODE32 was an ingenious system extension that worked around those flaws.\
\
SixtyFourSwitcher doesn't correct any design flaws, but it does allow you to get the most out of Snow Leopard's 64-bit addressing feature.\
\
